05523nam a22007695i 9781400852598DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2014    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008525987 a10.1515/97814008525982doi  a(DE-B1597)459878  a(OCoLC)984651064  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBF412b.J44 2017 7aHIS0130002bisacsh 7aLIT0041502bisacsh 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a153.9809442231 aJefferson, Ann, eauthor.10aGenius in France :bAn Idea and Its Uses /cAnn Jefferson.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2014] 4c©2015  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Enlightenment Genius -- tChapter 1: The Eighteenth Century: Mimesis and Effect -- tChapter 2: Genius Obscured: Diderot -- tPart II: Nineteenth-Century Genius: The Idiom of the Age -- tChapter 3: Language, Religion, Nation -- tChapter 4: Individual versus Collective Genius -- tChapter 5: The Romantic Poet and the Brotherhood of Genius -- tChapter 6: Victor Hugo, William Shakespeare, and the Dynasty of Genius -- tPart III: Genius in the Clinic -- tChapter 7: Genius under Observation: Lélut -- tChapter 8: Genius, Neurosis, and Family Trees: Moreau de Tours -- tChapter 9: Genius Restored to Health -- tPart IV: Failure, Femininity, and the Realist Novel -- tChapter 10: A Novel of Female Genius: Mme de Staël's Corinne -- tChapter 11: Balzac's Louis Lambert: Genius and the Feminine Mediator -- tChapter 12: Creativity and Procreation in Zola's L'OEuvre -- tPart V: Precocity and Child Prodigies -- tChapter 13: Exemplarity and Performance in Literature for Children -- tChapter 14: Alfred Binet and the Measurement of Intelligence -- tChapter 15: Minou Drouet: The Prodigy under Suspicion -- tPart VI: Genius in Theory -- tChapter 16: Cultural Critique and the End of Genius: Barthes, Sartre -- tChapter 17: The Return of Genius: Mad Poets -- tChapter 18: Julia Kristeva and Female Genius -- tChapter 19: Derrida, Cixous, and the Impostor -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex  aThis engaging book spans three centuries to provide the first full account of the long and diverse history of genius in France. Exploring a wide range of examples from literature, philosophy, and history, as well as medicine, psychology, and journalism, Ann Jefferson examines the ways in which the idea of genius has been ceaselessly reflected on and redefined through its uses in these different contexts. She traces its varying fortunes through the madness and imposture with which genius is often associated, and through the observations of those who determine its presence in others.Jefferson considers the modern beginnings of genius in eighteenth-century aesthetics and the works of philosophes such as Diderot. She then investigates the nineteenth-century notion of national and collective genius, the self-appointed role of Romantic poets as misunderstood geniuses, the recurrent obsession with failed genius in the realist novels of writers like Balzac and Zola, the contested category of female genius, and the medical literature that viewed genius as a form of pathology. She shows how twentieth-century views of genius narrowed through its association with IQ and child prodigies, and she discusses the different ways major theorists-including Sartre, Barthes, Derrida, and Kristeva-have repudiated and subsequently revived the concept.Rich in narrative detail, Genius in France brings a fresh approach to French intellectual and cultural history, and to the burgeoning field of genius studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aGeniuszFrancexHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBo